	<title>Exercises: Bases for a Subspace</title>
	
	<exercise>
		<problem>
			<para>For each of the vectors <latex>\Vect{x}</latex> below, find a vector <latex>\Vect{y}=(u,v)</latex> such that <latex>\EuScript{B}=\Set{ \Vect{x} , \Vect{y} }</latex> is a basis of <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>.</para>
		</problem>
		<part>
			<problem>
				<para><latex>\Vect{x} = (1,0)</latex></para>
			</problem>
			<approach>
				<answer><para>One possible choice is <latex>\Vect{y} = (0,1)</latex></para></answer>
				<solution.hint><para>Any vector which is not parallel to <latex>\Vect{x}</latex> will do.</para></solution.hint>
				<solution>
					<para>Any basis of <latex>\RNr[2]</latex> consists of two vectors because <latex>\RNr[2]</latex> has dimension <latex>2</latex>. So we just need to find a vector <latex>\Vect{y}</latex> which is not parallel to <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>. Possible choices of such vectors include</para>
					<computation>
						<left>\Vect{y}</left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>(0,1)</right>
						<left>\Vect{a}</left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>(0,17374)</right>
						<left>\Vect{b}</left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>(1,1)</right>
						<left>\Vect{c}</left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>(3,-4)</right>
					</computation>
				</solution>
			</approach>
		</part>
		
		<part>
			<problem>
				<para><latex>\Vect{x} = (1,1)</latex></para>
			</problem>
			<approach>
				<answer><para>One possible choice is <latex>\Vect{y} = (-1,1)</latex></para></answer>
				<solution.hint><para>Any vector which is not parallel to <latex>\Vect{x}</latex> will do.</para></solution.hint>
			</approach>
		</part>
		
		<part>
			<problem>
				<para><latex>\Vect{x} = (0,1)</latex></para>
			</problem>
			<approach>
				<answer><para>One possible choice is <latex>\Vect{y} = (1,0)</latex></para></answer>
			</approach>
		</part>
		
		<part>
			<problem>
				<para><latex>\Vect{x} = (7,3)</latex></para>
			</problem>
			<approach>
				<answer><para>One possible choice is <latex>\Vect{y} = (-4,0)</latex></para></answer>
			</approach>
		</part>
		
		<part>
			<problem>
				<para><latex>\Vect{x} = (2,-1)</latex></para>
			</problem>
		</part>
		
		<part>
			<problem>
				<para><latex>\Vect{x} = (-4,-1)</latex></para>
			</problem>
		</part>
		
		<part>
			<problem>
				<para><latex>\Vect{x} = (5,6)</latex></para>
			</problem>
		</part>
	</exercise>
	
	
	<exercise>
		<problem>
			<para>Given a nonzero vector <latex>\Vect{x}=(x,y)</latex> in <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>, find a vector <latex>\Vect{y}=(u,v)</latex> such that <latex>\EuScript{B}=\Set{ \Vect{x} , \Vect{y} }</latex> form a basis of <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>.</para>
		</problem>
		<approach>
			<answer><para>One possible choice is <latex>\Vect{y} := (-y,x)</latex>.</para></answer>
			<solution.hint><para>Recall that a set of nonzero orthogonal vectors is always linearly independent.</para></solution.hint>
			<solution.hint><para>Look for a nonzero vector <latex>\Vect{y}=(u,v)</latex> which is perpendicular to <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>.</para></solution.hint>
		</approach>
	</exercise>
	
	
	
	<exercise>	
		<problem>
			<para>For each of the vector pairs <latex>\Vect{x}</latex> and <latex>\Vect{y}</latex> in <latex>\RNr[3]</latex> below, find a vector <latex>\Vect{z}=(z_1,z_2,z_3)</latex> such that <latex>\EuScript{B}=\Set{ \Vect{x} , \Vect{y} , \Vect{z} }</latex> is a basis of <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>.</para>
		</problem>
		<part>
			<problem><para><latex>\Vect{x} = (1,0,0)</latex> and <latex>\Vect{y}=(0,1,0)</latex>.</para></problem>
			<approach>
				<answer><para>One possible choice is <latex>\Vect{z} = (0,0,1)</latex></para></answer>
				<solution.hint><para>Look for a vector which is perpendicular to <latex>\Vect{x}</latex> and <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>.</para></solution.hint>
				<solution.hint><para>Consider using the cross product operation to find a vector which is perpendicular to <latex>\Vect{x}</latex> and <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>.</para></solution.hint>
			</approach>
		</part>
		
		<part>
			<problem><para><latex>\Vect{x} = (1,0,1)</latex> and <latex>\Vect{y}=(1,1,1)</latex>.</para></problem>
			<approach>
				<answer><para>One possible choice is <latex>\Vect{z} = (1,0,0)</latex>. Another choice is <latex>\CrssPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{y} }</latex></para></answer>
			</approach>
		</part>
		
		<part>
			<problem><para><latex>\Vect{x} = (2,1,1)</latex> and <latex>\Vect{y}=(1,0,-1)</latex>.</para></problem>
		</part>
		
		<part>
			<problem><para><latex>\Vect{x} = (3,1,-2)</latex> and <latex>\Vect{y}=(-7,5,-2)</latex>.</para></problem>
		</part>
		
		<part>
			<problem><para><latex>\Vect{x} = (-1,-3,-4)</latex> and <latex>\Vect{y}=(2,2,2)</latex>.</para></problem>
		</part>
	</exercise>
	
	
	
	<exercise>	
		<problem>
			<para>Given linearly independent vectors <latex>\Vect{x}=(x_1,x_2,x_3)</latex> and <latex>\Vect{y}=(y_1,y_2,y_3)</latex> in <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>, find a vector <latex>\Vect{z}=(z_1,z_2,z_3)</latex> such that <latex>\EuScript{B}=\Set{ \Vect{x} , \Vect{y} , \Vect{z} }</latex> is a basis of <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>.</para>
		</problem>
		<approach>
			<answer>
				<para>One possible choice is <latex>\Vect{z} := \CrssPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{y} }</latex>.</para>
			</answer>
			<solution.hint><para>Look for a nonzero vector <latex>\Vect{z}=(z_1,z_2,z_3)</latex> which is perpendicular to <latex>\Vect{x}</latex> and <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>.</para></solution.hint>
			<solution.hint><para>Consider using the cross product.</para></solution.hint>
		</approach>
	</exercise>
	
	
	
	<exercise>	
		<problem>
			<para>For each of the vectors <latex>\Vect{x}</latex> in <latex>\RNr[3]</latex> below, find vectors <latex>\Vect{y}</latex> and <latex>\Vect{z}</latex> such that <latex>\EuScript{B}=\Set{ \Vect{x} , \Vect{y} , \Vect{z} }</latex> is a basis of <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>.</para>
		</problem>
		<part>
			<problem><para><latex>\Vect{x} = (1,0,0)</latex>.</para></problem>
			<approach>
				<answer><para>One possible choice is <latex>\Vect{y} = (0,1,0)</latex> and <latex>\Vect{z} = (0,0,1)</latex>.</para></answer>
				<solution.hint><para>First look for a vector <latex>\Vect{y}</latex> which is not parallel to <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>, so that <latex>\Vect{x}</latex> and <latex>\Vect{y}</latex> are linearly independent.</para></solution.hint>
				<solution.hint><para>Once you have linearly independent vectors <latex>\Vect{x}</latex> and <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>, consider using the cross product operation to find a vector which is perpendicular to <latex>\Vect{x}</latex> and <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>.</para></solution.hint>
			</approach>
		</part>
		
		<part>
			<problem><para><latex>\Vect{x} = (-1,0,1)</latex>.</para></problem>
		</part>
		
		<part>
			<problem><para><latex>\Vect{x} = (3,1,3)</latex>.</para></problem>
		</part>
		
		<part>
			<problem><para><latex>\Vect{x} = (0,1,2)</latex>.</para></problem>
		</part>
		
		<part>
			<problem><para><latex>\Vect{x} = (1,4,4)</latex>.</para></problem>
		</part>
	</exercise>
